---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";

const title = "About keptlocal — Private browser-only file tools";
const description = "The story behind keptlocal: why we built a privacy-first PDF and image toolkit that processes files entirely in your browser.";
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <Header />
  <main class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 pt-12 pb-16">
    <h1 class="font-display text-5xl tracking-tighter text-[var(--color-ink)] mb-4">About</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-[var(--color-ink-soft)] mb-10 leading-relaxed">
      keptlocal is a small set of privacy-first PDF and image tools that run entirely
      inside your browser. We're building it because every other free PDF tool on the
      internet asks you to upload your file to their server — and most people's files
      shouldn't have to take that trip.
    </p>

    <div class="prose-doc">
      <h2>What "kept local" actually means</h2>
      <p>
        When you use a typical online PDF tool, your file travels over the network to a server
        you've never seen, gets processed by code you can't audit, and comes back to you. The
        privacy policy says they delete it within a few hours. You take their word for it.
      </p>
      <p>
        keptlocal is built differently. The tools run on your device using WebAssembly — your
        browser does the work. Your file enters memory, gets transformed, and the result
        downloads. No part of it touches a network.
      </p>
      <p>
        This isn't a marketing claim — it's an architectural fact you can verify. Open your
        browser's Network tab (F12) while using any tool. You'll see the initial page load,
        and then no further activity. Zero uploads.
      </p>

      <h2>Who's behind this</h2>
      <p>
        keptlocal is built and maintained by Hiten Mahalwar, a software engineer with
        fifteen-plus years in healthcare IT. The site started as a side project after one
        too many friends asked "is it safe to upload my tax forms to that PDF site?" —
        and the honest answer was "probably, but you can't really know."
      </p>
      <p>
        Tools that respect your data shouldn't be a luxury. They should be the default.
      </p>

      <h2>How keptlocal stays free</h2>
      <p>
        The tools cost us almost nothing to run — your browser does the heavy lifting, and
        the rest is static files on a content delivery network. We show a small number of
        non-intrusive ads on the pages around the tools to cover hosting and domain costs.
        We don't put ads inside the tool itself.
      </p>
      <p>
        We don't:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Track you across sites</li>
        <li>Sell your data (we don't collect any to sell)</li>
        <li>Require accounts or email signups</li>
        <li>Use dark patterns to push you onto a paid plan</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        See our <a href="/privacy">privacy policy</a> for specifics.
      </p>

      <h2>What's coming</h2>
      <p>
        We're adding tools one or two at a time. The current roadmap covers the
        essentials — split, compress, rotate, convert, watermark, image resize and convert —
        and then a small set of AI-powered "smart" tools (PDF summarization, structured data
        extraction) for users who want them and explicitly opt in to a cloud-side option.
      </p>
      <p>
        Found a bug, want a tool, or have feedback? Reach us at our
        <a href="/contact">contact page</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
